 I mentioned this earlier in the case, so I should really have clarified it. The issue here is that, in order to avoid being a salary bill other than a legitimate expense, this sort of accounting treatment would require that I earn some ( significant? ) return on my money again by way of the businesss profit.  If I don't earn a significant return on my investment, drawing this money out would have the same effect as a salary, since I would net the same amount out of the business after closing out the deal  a negative outcome for me, from a financial perspective!
Now, I could be saying this wrong, and  salary doesnt equal the same thing as taking money out and using it as a return. In that event, I can pretty much ignore the distinction, and can take money out without worrying (ok, to a small degree, anyway) about fleeing my capacity as a principal-partowner.  (more over, moving money out of the business would practically make me a paid employee!) So the bottom line is, there ought to be enough profit coming in so I can use the money to survive; otherwise there are issues to consider  thanks for pointing this out, although I never mentioned it before (`moreover) that part of the question posted;
If using this money somehow kills the business or prohibits realization of profit with regards to potential future partnerships I am effectively rendered unemployed. At, IRR < 10 percent or so I am
